canonical:
  title: 貴公子眞草帖
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 奇才妙翰今古稀蘭亭無人子昴非千年大雅氣像豪風流冠映一代高牙籤萬軸銀鉤字淸讌日夕供翫戲有時臨池發興新筆意所到皆精神晴䆫烏几龍臍香鵝紈滿眼霜雪光玉蜍點滴淸露硏縱橫掃盡生雲烟勢快新驚風雲驟氣徤忽作蛟龍闘變化三體各臻妙玉樹瓊柯相照耀日窮百紙思愈壯散入家家作屛幛中原文章二閣老一見喜得王與趙粲粲袖有驪珠好亦知海外有奇寶持向京華索高價從使聲名滿天下君不見昔時唐宗購晉跡虹光夜夜燭秘閣又不見大明天子喜妙手刻取堅垊傳不朽中閒作者安足計已喚顔柳作奴隷嗟我不是具眼者胡乃搥胸血如瀉從來嗜好亦在此願得一本比禽李
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 貴公子眞草帖
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 奇才妙翰今古稀。蘭亭無人子昴非。千年大雅氣像豪。風流冠映一代高。牙籤萬軸銀鉤字。淸讌日夕供翫戲。有時臨池發興新。筆意所到皆精神。晴䆫烏几龍臍香。鵝紈滿眼霜雪光。玉蜍點滴淸露硏。縱橫掃盡生雲烟。勢快新驚風雲驟。氣徤忽作蛟龍闘。變化三體各臻妙。玉樹瓊柯相照耀。日窮百紙思愈壯。散入家家作屛幛。中原文章二閣老。一見喜得王與趙。粲粲袖有驪珠好。亦知海外有奇寶。持向京華索高價。從使聲名滿天下。君不見昔時唐宗購晉跡。虹光夜夜燭秘閣。又不見大明天子喜妙手。刻取堅垊傳不朽。中閒作者安足計。已喚顔柳作奴隷。嗟我不是具眼者。胡乃搥胸血如瀉。從來嗜好亦在此。願得一本比禽李。
korean:
  title: 귀공자 진초첩
  author: 서거정
  language: kor
  text: |-
    기특한 재주 묘한 글씨 고금에 드문것
    난정엔 사람 없고 조자앙도 아닐세
    천년 대아의 기상이 호방하니
    그 높은 풍류가 일대에 관절했네
    아첨 만축의 은구같은 글씨들을
    조석에 조용할 때 구경하며 희롱타가
    때로는 벼루를 대하여 새 홍치를 발하니
    필의가 이르는 곳에 모두 다 신묘
    맑은 창 감정 책상에 용제향을 피워 놓고
    아환을 펼치니 눈에 가득한 상설 빛
    옥 두꺼비 연적의 이슬을 따라 갈아
    이리 저리 쓸어내니 운연이 생기누나
    쾌한 형세는 풍운이 새로 놀라 휘몰아치는 듯
    건장한 기운은 교룡이 문득 싸우는 듯
    변화하는 삼체가 모두 묘에 이르러
    옥수ㆍ경가가 서로 비춰 찬란하네
    날마다 백 장을 써도 생각 더욱 장하여
    흩어져 집집에 들어 병장이 되는구나
    중원의 문장 두 각로가
    한번 보자 왕희지ㆍ조맹부를 얻었다 기뻐하며
    소매속에 찬란하게 여의주를 넣고 갔으니
    해외(조선)에도 이러한 기보있음을 알리리
    북경으로 가져다가 비싼 값을 달래서
    이 서가의 명성이 천하에 가득케 되었네
    그대는 보지 못했는가. 옛날 당태종이 왕우군의 진적을 얻어서
    무지개 빛이 밤마다 비각을 환하게 했던 것을
    또 보지 못했는가. 대명 천자가 묘한 글씨 좋아하여
    비석에 새겨 불후에 전하도록 한 것을
    중간의 모모 서가 쯤 문제가 되리
    안노공ㆍ유공권 쯤 이미 노복이라 부르네
    아 내야말고 구안자가 아닌데
    어찌 이리 가슴을 치며 피를 쏟듯 하는가
    내 기호도 종래 이에 있으니
    원컨대 한 본을 얻어서 금리에 견주과저
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1400_010_0140&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 두 각로(閣老) : '
    value: 그때에 마침 중국에서 두 사신이 와서 안평대군의 글씨를 칭찬하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 垊 : '
    value: 《사가시집(四佳詩集》 권3에는 '珉'으로 되어 있다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 금리(禽李) : '
    value: 왕희지(王羲之)의 필적에 내금청리첩(來禽靑李帖)이 있다.
english:
  title: On the Calligraphy of the Virtuous Prince
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Rare talent and wondrous brushwork, seldom seen across the ages—
    No equal now walks where Orchid Pavilion stands, not even Zhao Mengfu.
    For a thousand years the great elegance breathes with noble force,
    And such lofty refinement crowns the highest of this generation.

    Thousands of volumes bound in jade labels, silver-hook script gleaming,
    Each evening leisure brings these treasures forth for quiet admiration.
    When he draws near the inkstone, new inspiration springs alive,
    And wherever the brush arrives, all blooms with divine spirit.

    In the luminous study, incense of dragon-brain curls from the stand,
    The silken page unfolds to fill the eye with frost and snow's bright gleam.
    The jade toad of the water-dropper grinds the dew to liquid grace,
    And sweeping strokes release clouds and mists that dance and swirl.

    The momentum rushes quick, as wind and cloud suddenly surge,
    The robust force rolls forth as if two dragons clash and fight.
    Three scripts transformed, each achieving utmost mastery,
    Jade trees and crystal boughs reflected, brilliant and resplendent.

    Day after day he fills a hundred pages, his spirit ever greater,
    Scattered now to every household as folding screens and scrolls.
    When those two chancellors of the central realm came calling,
    They saw and rejoiced—praising Wang Xizhi and Zhao Mengfu both.

    The gems shine radiant in his sleeve, pearls of luminous worth,
    So the lands beyond the seas came to know of such rare treasure.
    Carried toward the capital, its price grew ever higher,
    And thus this master's name spread wide across the realm.

    Have you not heard how Tang Taizong once sought the traces of Jin masters?
    How each night rainbow light illumined his secret repository?
    Have you not heard how the great Ming Emperor cherished skillful hands,
    And had their art carved into stone that time could not devour?

    Why should lesser scribes then merit mention in this age?
    Already Yan and Liu are summoned forth as servants now.
    Yet I—though not possessed of the keen eye of true connoisseurs—
    Why do I strike my chest and feel my blood flow forth like water?

    For my own love has ever dwelt in this same sacred art,
    And I desire but one scroll to compare with those of Wang and Li.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Orchid Pavilion (蘭亭): The legendary gathering of scholars at which Wang Xizhi composed his famous preface, considered the pinnacle of calligraphic achievement.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhao Mengfu (趙孟頫): The great Yuan Dynasty calligrapher, frequently invoked as a standard of excellence in East Asian tradition.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three scripts (三體): Seal script (篆書), clerical script (隸書), and running script (行書).'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Two chancellors (中原文章二閣老): Chinese envoys who reportedly praised Prince Anpyeong''s calligraphy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wang Xizhi and Zhao Mengfu: The poem refers to ''The Orchid Pavilion Preface'' and other works by these masters as incomparable standards.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Tang Taizong: Emperor of Tang Dynasty, famous for his passion for collecting calligraphy and paintings of the Jin Dynasty.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yan and Liu: Yan Zhenqing and Liu Gongquan, legendary Tang Dynasty calligraphers now referenced as historical standards.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Wang and Li (禽李): References to Wang Xizhi''s ''Coming to the Birds and Green Pear Tree Scroll'' and other masterworks by the great ancient calligraphers.'
